'''Candy Alt Crowley''' (born December 26, 1948) is an American [[news anchor]] who was employed as [[CNN]]'s chief political [[Reporter|correspondent]], specializing in USA national and state elections. She was based in CNN's [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] bureau and was the anchor of their Sunday morning talk show ''[[State of the Union with Candy Crowley]]''. She has covered elections for over two decades.{{fact|date=November 2013}}

==Early life and education==
Crowley was born in [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo]], Michigan, Where her family had moved briefly from [[St. Louis]], Missouri. Her family moved back to St. Louis when she was a toddler and she grew up in the St. Louis County suburb of [[Creve Coeur, Missouri|Creve Coeur]], Missouri.<ref>{{cite news|last=Angel|first=Traci|title=Catching Up With...Candy Crowley|url=http://www.stlmag.com/St-Louis-Magazine/January-2005/Catching-Up-With-Candy-Crowley/#|newspaper=St.&nbsp;Louis Magazine|date=January 2005}}</ref> She attended kindergarten through high school at The Principia School in St. Louis County where she graduated in 1966. After high school she attended [[Randolph-Macon Woman's College]] in [[Lynchburg, Virginia|Lynchburg]], [[Virginia]], where she graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[English major|English]].<ref name="CNN bio"/>

==Career==
Crowley started her career as a newsroom assistant with the [[Washington, D.C.]]-based radio station [[WASH-FM|WASH&#8209;FM]].{{fact|date=November 2013}} She was an [[News presenter|anchor]] for [[Mutual Broadcasting System|Mutual Broadcasting]] and the White House correspondent for the [[Associated Press]].<ref name="CNN bio">{{cite web|title=Anchors & Reporters: Candy Crowley|url=http://www.cnn.com/CNN/anchors_reporters/crowley.candy.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 19, 2012}}</ref> She moved from [[NBC]] to [[CNN]] in 1987.<ref name="LA Times">{{cite news|last=Rainey|first=James|title=She's lighter 'in a lot of ways'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/18/entertainment/et-onthemedia18|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=November 18, 2009}}</ref> She hosted ''Inside Politics'' in place of [[Judy Woodruff]] before the show was replaced with ''[[The Situation Room]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saying Goodbye To Inside Politics|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/saying-goodbye-to-inside-politics_b6114|newspaper=TVNewser|date=August 5, 2005}}</ref> In February 2010, Crowley succeeded [[John King (journalist)|John King]] as an anchor of the Sunday morning political talk show ''[[State of the Union with Candy Crowley|State of the Union]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crowley to take over State of the Union anchor chair|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2010/01/31/crowley-to-take-over-state-of-the-union-anchor-chair/|newspaper=CNN|date=January 31, 2010}}</ref>

Crowley has been characterized by the ''Los Angeles Times'' as a "straight shooter", her career as "sophisticated political observation, graceful writing, and determined fairness," and her style as "no-nonsense". The ''L.A. Times'' article says that because of this criticism of her reporting is equally distributed between the Democratic and Republican parties.<ref name="LA Times"/>

Crowley has won several awards, including the Broadcasters’ Award from the [[Associated Press]], the 2003 and 1998 Dirksen Awards from the [[National Press Foundation]], the 1997 and 2005 Joan Shorenstein Barone Award, a 2003 [[Emmy Award]] for her work on CNN Presents Enemy Within, the 2004 [[Gracie Awards|Gracie Allen Award]] for her war coverage, a [[National Headliner Awards|National Headliner]] and a Cine award, the 2005 [[RTNDA Edward R. Murrow Award|Edward R. Murrow Award]], and the 2012 William Allen White Foundation National Citation from the school of journalism at the University of Kansas for her expertise on "politics, politicians, and the events that have changed the world."<ref>{{cite news |first=Natasha |last=Veseer |publisher=KU Press Release |title=Political correspondent Candy Crowley to receive William Allen White citation |date=January 25, 2012 |url=http://archive.news.ku.edu/2012/january/25/crowley.shtml}}</ref>

Crowley served as the moderator October 16, 2012 for the [[Second U.S. presidential debate of 2012|second presidential election debate]] between President [[Barack Obama]] and his [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] opponent [[Mitt Romney]].<ref name=blake>{{cite news|last=Blake|first=Aaron|title=Presidential Debate Moderators Announced: Crowley Is First Woman in 20 Years|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/post/presidential-debate-moderators-announced-crowley-is-first-woman-in-20-years/2012/08/13/0e327af6-e553-11e1-8f62-58260e3940a0_blog.html|newspaper=Washington Post|date=August 13, 2012}}</ref> She received both criticism and praise for interjecting during the debate regarding the [[attack on the U.S. diplomatic mission in Benghazi]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Russell |last=Goldman |title=Candy Crowley Defends Her Libya Comment During Presidential Debate |date=October 17, 2012 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/candy-crowley-defends-libya-comment-presidential-debate/story?id=17500587 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Neil |last=Munro |title=Obama dodges Benghazi bullet as debate descends into semantics |publisher=The Daily Caller |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 19, 2013 |url=http://dailycaller.com/2012/10/17/obama-dodges-benghazi-bullet-as-debate-descends-into-semantics}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=George |last=Stephanopolous |title=Greta Van Susteren: Candy Crowley ‘Clumsy’ on Benghazi Debate Interjection |date=October 21, 2012 |publisher=ABC News |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/10/greta-van-susteren-candy-crowley-clumsy-on-benghazi-debate-interjection/ |accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Bryan |last=Monroe |title=The truth about what Candy Crowley said |date=October 20, 2012 |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/10/18/politics/fact-check-crowley-critics-debate |accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> Controversy arose when Crowley backed Obama's claim he stated the Benghazi attack was the result of terrorism, when her network news agency, CNN, had previously reported on September 21, 2012 that Obama only described the Benghazi attacks as terrorism "for the first time" on September 20, nine days following the attacks. <ref>{{cite news |first= CNN |last= Wire Staff |title= Clinton: No sign that Stevens believed he was on an al Qaeda hit list |date=September 21, 2012 |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/20/world/africa/libya-investigation/index.html}}</ref> She was the first woman to moderate a presidential debate since [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s [[Carole Simpson]] in [[United States presidential election, 1992|1992]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Annie |last=Groer |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/she-the-people/wp/2012/10/11/moderators/ |title=There have actually been three — count ‘em, three — female moderators of presidential debates |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=October 11, 2012 |accessdate=June 9, 2013}}</ref>

On March 17, 2013, following their CNN report on the guilty verdict of two [[Steubenville, Ohio|Steubenville]] high school football players for the [[Steubenville High School rape case|rape of an unconscious sixteen-year-old]], Crowley and fellow journalist [[Poppy Harlow]] were criticized for giving too much coverage to how the verdict would affect the defendants' lives.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Knowles |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/cnn-rape-coverage-sparks-petition-article-1.1292387 |title=Petition blasting CNN for allegedly sympathetic coverage of Steubenville, Ohio, rape convicts garners more than 200,000 signatures |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=March 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 9, 2013}}</ref><ref >{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2013/03/18/cnn-is-getting-hammered-for-steubenville-coverage |title=CNN is getting hammered for Steubenville coverage |first=Erik |last=Wemple |date=March 18, 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=June 9, 2013}}</ref>

CNN announced on December 5, 2014 Crowley's decision to leave the network after 27 years.  CNN Worldwide President [[Jeff Zucker]] said Crowley "has made the decision to move on, so she can embark on the next chapter of her already prolific career. As difficult as it is for us to imagine CNN without Candy, we know that she comes to this decision thoughtfully, and she has our full support." <ref>{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Bradner |title=Crowley to leave CNN after 27 years |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/05/politics/candy-crowley-leaving-cnn/index.html?hpt=hp_t2 |accessdate=December 6, 2014}}</ref>  Her last broadcast was on ''State of the Union'' on December 21, 2014.<ref>{{cite web
| url        = http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/21/sotu-crowley-candy-says-goodbye-after-27-years.cnn.html?hpt=hp_t2
